                    <msContents>
                        <summary>A complete copy of the <title>Būstān</title> (Fragrant Orchard) by
                                <persName role="aut" xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" type="standard"
                                key="person_100206721" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/100206721/">Saʻdī
                                Shīrazī (ca. 1213–1292)</persName>, one of the most revered works by
                            this preeminent Persian Ṣūfī poet, which he composed in <date
                                calendar="#Gregorian" when="1257">655 AH (1257 CE)</date>. Together
                            with his <title>Gulistān</title> (Rose Garden), both the literary style
                            and structure of the work profoundly influenced subsequent writers. The
                            work opens with an introduction in which the author praises God and his
                            patrons, the Salghurd-era rulers of Fars province from their capital at
                                <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7002148"
                                >Shiraz</placeName>, <persName role="dte" key="person_f3730">Saʿd I
                                (Saʿd ibn Zangī, r. 1198–1226)</persName>, his son <persName
                                role="dte" key="person_f7846">Abū Bakr ibn Saʿd ibn Zangī (r.
                                1226–1260)</persName>, and grandson <persName role="dte"
                                key="person_f7847">Muḥammad bin Abū Bakr ibn Saʿd ibn Zangī (fl.
                                13th c.)</persName>. The text comprises ten chapters on topics such
                            as ethics, government, love, contentment, humility, repentance, and
                            other subjects, embellished throughout with anecdotes and tales from the
                            author's life and travels. Famed Mughal-era court calligrapher <persName
                                xml:lang="fa-latn-x-lc" role="scr"
                                key="person_189148521984620851178">Muḥammad Ḥusayn Kashmīrī, known
                                as <addName>Zarrīn Qalam</addName></persName> copied this volume.
                            While it bears part of the original illuminated headpiece, it appears
                            otherwise unfinished, for it lacks any other headers. Subsequently
                            acquired by <persName role="fmo seal" key="person_f8663">William Jackson
                                (1753–1807)</persName>, who served for 30 years in Calcutta until
                            his death in <date>1807</date>, then <persName role="fmo ins ato"
                                ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/66868844" key="person_66868844">James Ross
                                (1759–1831)</persName>, who translated the <title>Gulistan</title>
                            and intended to publish his translation this work as well; however, he
                            passed away before he completed it.</summary>


